excerpt: Petite France is the city's lively tourist hub, known for cobblestone streets, canals, and well-preserved half-timbered homes like the Tanners’ House, built in 1572. A terrace atop the 17th-century Barrage Vauban, a covered bridge and dam, offers panoramic views. Alsatian eateries dot the area, while shops on and around Grand’Rue sell clothing and souvenirs such as crockery, wine, and specialty teas.
detail_description: Petite-France is a charming and vibrant area in Strasbourg, featuring cobblestone streets, canals, and well-preserved half-timbered houses. The Tanners’ House, dating back to 1572, is a notable historical site. Visitors can enjoy panoramic views from the terrace atop the 17th-century Barrage Vauban.
name: Petite-France

detail_description: The Palais Rohan, located on the Grande Ile in Strasbourg, is a historic monument that was originally a princely residence for the Rohan family. Today, it houses three museums: an art museum, an archeology museum, and a decorative arts museum. Even if you don't plan to visit the museums, it's worth visiting to admire the stunning architecture and facade of the palace.
name: Palais Rohan

excerpt: Flower-filled park dating to the 17th century, with boating lake, water birds & terrace restaurant.
detail_description: Parc de l'Orangerie is a charming park located in Strasbourg, dating back to the 17th century. Situated near the European Parliament and the Court of Human Rights, it boasts a rich history that dates back to the French Revolution. Originally home to 140 orange trees confiscated from Chateau de Bouxwiller, only three of these trees remain today and can be seen in the park's greenhouses on certain days.
name: Parc de l'Orangerie

excerpt: Strasbourg's main square, featuring an expansive pedestrian area with shops & cafes along the sides.
detail_description: Place Kléber is Strasbourg's main square, offering a spacious pedestrian area lined with shops and cafes. The square hosts the famous Christkindelsmarik de Strasbourg Christmas market, featuring an impressive fir tree that marks the beginning of the festive season. This market is part of eleven markets spread across central Strasbourg, each with its own specialties but all offering ornaments, gifts, pottery, linens, foods, mulled wine, and the city's symbolic storks.
name: Place Kléber

excerpt: Completed in 1999, the official seat of the European Parliament offers tours & interactive exhibits.
detail_description: The European Parliament in Strasbourg, completed in 1999, is located in the eastern part of France near the German border. As the capital of the Great East region, it boasts a unique blend of German-French cultures. The city's Notre-Dame Cathedral and historic center, designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site, are major attractions. Visitors can explore Petite France with its charming half-timbered houses and footbridges before heading to the European District.
name: European Parliament | Strasbourg

excerpt: Pink sandstone weir & bridge built in the 17th century, now housing historic sculptures.
detail_description: Barrage Vauban, a 17th-century pink sandstone weir and bridge in Strasbourg, was originally constructed as a defensive structure to protect the city from potential attacks. Today, it stands as a historic site housing sculptures and artwork. The panoramic viewpoint at the tip of the dam offers stunning views of the city, including Le Petite France and the Ponts Couverts.
name: Barrage Vauban
address: Pl. du Qur Blanc, 67000 Strasbourg, France

excerpt: Gothic edifice, dating from the 1200s, with a 16th-century astronomical clock & a rose window.
detail_description: The Cathédrale Notre-Dame-de-Strasbourg is a stunning Gothic edifice that dates back to the 1200s and features a remarkable 16th-century astronomical clock and a beautiful rose window. Its iconic 142-meter spire can be seen towering over the city's rooftops, making it an unmissable landmark.
name: Cathédrale Notre-Dame-de-Strasbourg
address: Pl. de la Cathédrale, 67000 Strasbourg, France

excerpt: Strasbourg is the capital city of the Grand Est region, formerly Alsace, in northeastern France. It's also the formal seat of the European Parliament and sits near the German border, with culture and architecture blending German and French influences. Its Gothic Cathédrale Notre-Dame features daily shows from its astronomical clock and sweeping views of the Rhine River from partway up its 142m spire.
detail_description: Strasbourg, the capital city of the Grand Est region in northeastern France, is a captivating blend of German and French influences. It's renowned for its Gothic Cathédrale Notre-Dame with its astronomical clock and stunning views of the Rhine River. The city also serves as the formal seat of the European Parliament.
name: Strasbourg

excerpt: Museum set in 16th- & 17th-century mansions, with displays on Alsatian art, folklore & rural life.
detail_description: The Alsatian Museum is a captivating collection housed in interconnected 16th- and 17th-century mansions, offering a glimpse into the history of Alsace. With over 5,000 artifacts and artworks, the museum paints a vivid picture of daily life in the region during the 18th and 19th centuries. Visitors can explore traditional clothing, homeware, tools, toys, furniture, religious artifacts across its 30 rooms.
name: Alsatian Museum

excerpt: Museum tracing city's urban, social & political history with models, paintings & daily-life objects.
detail_description: The Historical Museum of the City of Strasbourg, housed in the former slaughterhouse since 1920, offers a comprehensive journey through the city's urban, social, and political history. The museum boasts an extensive collection including scale models like the plan-relief of 1727 depicting the city and its surroundings, paintings, military weapons and uniforms, as well as everyday objects.
name: Historical Museum of the City of Strasbourg

excerpt: Contemporary glass-fronted museum with modern art, photography & installations, plus a terrace cafe.
detail_description: The Strasbourg Museum of Modern and Contemporary Art is a striking glass-fronted museum showcasing modern art, photography, and installations. Situated near the Covered Bridges, it offers an expansive collection spanning from Impressionism to contemporary works. Visitors can admire pieces by renowned artists such as Monet, Picasso, Klee, and Rodin. The museum's temporary exhibitions add further depth to its offerings. Additionally, the terrace cafe provides a delightful dining option with picturesque views.
name: Strasbourg Museum of Modern and Contemporary Art

excerpt: Island in the center of Strasbourg, with churches, palaces & tourist draws such as hotels & shops.
detail_description: Grande-Île de Strasbourg, located in the heart of the city, is a renowned historical center and the first to be entirely classified as a UNESCO World Heritage Site. This island is home to an array of attractions including churches, palaces, hotels, and shops. The city itself boasts a population of nearly half a million people and spans across the river into Germany.
name: Grande-Île de Strasbourg

excerpt: Neustadt, or the German Quarter, is known for the Prussian-style buildings surrounding the formal gardens of Place de la République, including the National Theater and University Library. The Tomi Ungerer Museum shows drawings and sculptures by the Alsatian illustrator. By the River Ill, the Gallia university area is popular for its family-friendly attractions and Botanical Garden, with an arboretum and greenhouses.
detail_description: Neustadt, also known as the German Quarter, is a district in Strasbourg characterized by its Prussian-style architecture and formal gardens. The area is home to notable attractions such as the National Theater, University Library, and Tomi Ungerer Museum showcasing works by the Alsatian illustrator. Along the River Ill, visitors can explore the family-friendly Gallia university area with its Botanical Garden featuring an arboretum and greenhouses.
name: Neustadt

excerpt: Protestant church featuring a vaulted Gothic interior, 14th-century frescoes & a verdant cloister.
detail_description: Located near Iron Man Square, Église Saint-Pierre-le-Jeune is a Protestant church with a rich history dating back to the 7th century. The church features a charming cloister that was renovated in 2005 and boasts arcade galleries dating as far back as 1031. Its interior is adorned with stunning vaults and vibrant frescoes from the 14th and 15th centuries, making it one of Strasbourg's oldest and most captivating sites.
name: Église Saint-Pierre-le-Jeune

excerpt: Set of 3 bridges & 4 towers built during the 13th century, in a charming setting with scenic views.
detail_description: The Strasbourg Covered Bridges, a set of three bridges and four towers dating back to the 13th century, are located in a charming setting with scenic views. Despite losing their roofs in the 18th century, they still retain their name. The four towers overlooking the bridges date from the 14th century and were part of the city's former ramparts. These historic structures have been classified as a Monument historique since 1928.
name: Strasbourg Covered Bridges

excerpt: Large riverfront garden & cultural center with a pedestrian bridge linking French & German sides.
detail_description: Jardin des Deux Rives, also known as The Two Shores Garden, is a sprawling riverfront park that spans across both the French and German sides of the Rhine. This expansive 370-acre garden is connected by the Bridge of Europe, symbolizing the friendship between France and Germany. Visitors can easily walk from Strasbourg, France to Kehl, Germany in just a minute.
name: Jardin des Deux Rives

detail_description: The Christmas Market in Strasbourg, located in the Alsace region of France, is often hailed as the best in Europe. The market offers an enchanting atmosphere with stunning decorations that capture the spirit of Noel and Christmas. Visitors can explore the beautiful markets around the Cathedral Notre Dame and enjoy traditional Alsatian cuisine at restaurants like 'le tir de bouchon.' While parking may be a challenge due to crowds, accessing downtown and other locations is convenient by train.
name: Christmas market

excerpt: Landmark vaulted cellar from 1395, offering wine tastings & tours past giant, aged barrels.
detail_description: Nestled beneath the Strasbourg Hospital, the Cave Historique des Hospices de Strasbourg is a remarkable landmark that dates back to 1395. This historic cellar offers visitors an enchanting glimpse into the past, showcasing a collection of around 60 majestic oak barrels filled with exquisite Alsatian wines. The unique origin of these wines stems from a time when patients would pay for their medical care with land and vineyards, making wine not just a beverage but also an essential part of both religious and medicinal practices.
name: Cave Historique des Hospices de Strasbourg

excerpt: Educational & play space including a garden with science & sensory trails, a pond & an orchard.
detail_description: Le Vaisseau, situated in Strasbourg, is a science discovery center designed for children aged 3 to 15. The museum offers around 130 interactive displays and activities covering various topics such as the human body, plants and animals, building and construction, mathematics, and logic. Visitors can explore the garden with science and sensory trails, a pond, and an orchard.
name: Le Vaisseau
address: 1 Bis Rue Philippe Dollinger, 67100 Strasbourg, France

excerpt: Historic Protestant church with late-Gothic design, tombs & an organ played by Mozart.
detail_description: St. Thomas Church, also known as the Protestant Cathedral, is a significant landmark in Strasbourg with a rich historical and cultural legacy. It became the main Protestant church in the region after Cathedrale Notre-Dame transitioned to Catholicism in 1681. The church's late-Gothic design and pink sandstone exterior make it emblematic of Alsatian Gothic architecture. It features tombs and an organ that was played by Mozart.
name: St. Thomas Church

excerpt: Displays on birds, insects & mammals from the Arctic to the Andes, including preserved specimens.
detail_description: The Strasbourg Zoological Museum, located in the city's University campus, houses a diverse collection of preserved specimens representing wildlife from around the world. Established in the 18th century with Jean Hermann's natural history collection, the museum offers visitors a journey through different climates and ecosystems, showcasing animals from the Arctic to the Andes. As you stroll through its galleries, you can immerse yourself in the rich biodiversity of various regions and gain insights into their natural habitats.
name: Strasbourg Zoological Museum
address: 29 Bd de la Victoire, 67000 Strasbourg, France

excerpt: Museum dedicated to French illustrator Tomi Ungerer with both kid-friendly & erotic graphic works.
detail_description: The Tomi Ungerer Museum-International Illustration Centre in Strasbourg is a unique museum dedicated to the works of French illustrator Tomi Ungerer. The museum houses an impressive collection of 800 drawings by Ungerer, showcasing his diverse artistic talents. Visitors can explore both kid-friendly and more provocative graphic works, offering a comprehensive look at the artist's career. Located on Avenue de la Marseillaise, this cultural hub provides an enriching experience for art enthusiasts and families alike.
name: Tomi Ungerer Museum-International Illustration Centre
address: 2 Av. de la Marseillaise, 67000 Strasbourg, France

excerpt: Museum tracing the city's social & political history from the Middle Ages to the French Revolution.
detail_description: The Musée de l'Œuvre-Notre-Dame is a captivating museum located at the foot of the Notre Dame Cathedral in Strasbourg. Housed in a remarkable half-medieval, half-Renaissance building, it offers a journey through seven centuries of artistic development in the Upper Rhine region. The museum's collection includes upper-Rhenish art dating back to 1681, featuring sculptures, stained-glass windows, and architectural fragments from Strasbourg Cathedral.
name: Musée de l'Œuvre-Notre-Dame

excerpt: Notable fine arts gallery on first floor of the elegant, former Bishop's Palace, built in the 1730s.
detail_description: The Strasbourg Museum of Fine Arts is housed in the former Bishop's Palace, a grand 18th-century building. On its first floor, visitors can explore a remarkable collection of European masterpieces spanning from the Middle Ages to modern times. The palace's lower level is home to the Museum of Decorative Arts, showcasing ceramics, porcelain, and goldsmith pieces alongside the bishops' chambers, chapel, and library. Additionally, the Archaeological Museum exhibits artifacts from prehistory to the Middle Ages.
name: Strasbourg Museum of Fine Arts

excerpt: Set in a unique water tower, this museum showcases a collection of more than 1,000 voodoo artifacts.
detail_description: Nestled within a striking 19th-century water tower, the Château Musée Vodou in Strasbourg offers an extraordinary glimpse into the world of voodoo. This unique museum is home to over 1,000 artifacts from West African countries such as Ghana, Benin, Togo, and Nigeria. Each piece tells a story of cultural significance—used for religious ceremonies, medicinal purposes, and even witchcraft.
name: Château Musée Vodou

detail_description: Batorama, a popular boat tour company in Strasbourg, offers a relaxing cruise along the River Ill. The journey begins at the quay near Palais Rohan and takes about an hour to complete. Passengers will navigate through two locks and venture towards the European Quarter, passing through the historic Neustadt district known for its diverse architecture. For those interested in shopping for souvenirs, the area surrounding the cathedral is recommended.
name: Batorama
address: 18 Pl. de la Cathédrale, 67000 Strasbourg, France

excerpt: This grand 19th-century train station with modern frontage offers transportation, dining & shops.
detail_description: Strasbourg is a vibrant city with a grand 19th-century train station that offers modern amenities, dining options, and shops. The Train Station quarter is conveniently located just a short walk from La Petite France and the city center, making it an ideal spot for travelers arriving by train or plane. All tram lines pass through this neighborhood, providing easy access to explore every part of the city.
name: Strasbourg

excerpt: Riverside mosque built in a modern style, with conferences & capacity for over 1,000 worshipers.
detail_description: The Grande Mosquée de Strasbourg is a large, modern mosque that accommodates over 1,000 worshippers. The mosque features elegant architecture and an impressive copper dome. It is situated on a bend in the River Ill and is flanked by beautiful gardens. The women's area of prayer is spacious and well-equipped, and the wudhu area is spotless. The mosque has a big parking lot for drivers who come by car.
name: Grande Mosquée de Strasbourg

detail_description: Krutenau, located just south of Strasbourg's city center, is a vibrant and diverse neighborhood that appeals to young travelers and those seeking a contemporary experience. It's popular among young professionals, students, and anyone looking for an eclectic atmosphere. The area boasts trendy bars, cozy cafes, and unique boutique shops. Krutenau is also known for its dynamic street art scene and numerous galleries, making it a hub for creatives.
name: Krutenau

excerpt: Innovative fine dining in an elegant 19th-century venue with a huge painting by Adolphe Grison.
detail_description: Au Crocodile is a renowned restaurant located in an elegant 19th-century venue, offering innovative fine dining with a touch of old Alsace and a modern twist. The grand salon features skylights and a magnificent 19th-century painting by Adolphe Grison, setting the tone for an exquisite dining experience. Chef Romain Brillat leads the team in presenting dazzling dishes that showcase Alsatian-French haute cuisine with a nouvelle spin.
name: Au Crocodile

detail_description: Discover the historic cellars of Strasbourg at the medieval Hospices, where wine has been produced and stored since 1395. The proceeds supported a charitable hospital and almshouse, providing shelter, food, and medical care to the needy. Take a boat tour on the canals departing from Rohan Palace with Batorama for an all-weather experience. Explore the old town's culture through a walking food tour visiting 4 restaurants/bars to taste local specialties.
name: One City Tours - Visite de Strasbourg à Segway
address: 5 Pt Rue du Vieux Marché aux Vins, 67000 Strasbourg, France

detail_description: The Palais de l'Europe, designed by French architect Henry Bernard and opened in 1977, serves as the main building of the Conseil de l'Europe. Its exterior features a solid, fortress-like design with flags of member states at the entrance, symbolizing unity and trust. The structure is part of Strasbourg's European district, which includes other important European institutions like the European Parliament and various administrative buildings.
name: Conseil de l'Europe

detail_description: Place Broglie in Strasbourg is located near the cathedral and hosts a market on Saturdays from 7:00 to 13:00. Visitors can find a variety of Alsatian products, food, and specialties at this vibrant marketplace.
name: Place Broglie
Ophorus Day Trips & Wine Tours in Alsace
address: Z.A DU Mittelfeld, 2 Rue Alfred Kastler 67300, 67300 Strasbourg, France

detail_description: Experience the magic of Christmas in Alsace with a visit to Strasbourg in December. Take a guided tour to discover the city's enchanting illuminations, beautifully decorated houses, and the famous Christmas market. Don't miss Un Noel en Alsace, a charming year-round Christmas shop offering moderately priced ornaments in a winter wonderland setting. Known as the 'Capital of Christmas,' Strasbourg hosts one of Europe's largest Christmas markets with plenty of local shops for unique presents.
name: Christmas in Alsace

detail_description: La Petite France is a charming area located just south of the Grande Ile in Strasbourg, between two rivers. It's known for its picturesque streets filled with half-timbered houses, making it a favorite spot for visitors to capture beautiful photos. The area is also home to numerous shops, including those within the museums, offering unique souvenirs.
name: La Petite France
Winstub le Platz
address: 7 Pl. de la Cathédrale, 67000 Strasbourg, France

detail_description: Strasbourg bike tours show you the city's highlights from different angles, starting with the charming old town and going on to explore the interesting neighbourhoods of Petite France and Neustadt. You'll see some of Strasbourg's most important landmarks, like the cathedral and palaces, as well as its picturesque streets.
name: Strasbourg bike tours

detail_description: Quai des Bateliers, located in Strasbourg near Krutenau, is a serene and charming area perfect for spending a leisurely afternoon. It offers a peaceful ambiance with quaint shops and cozy cafes along the waterfront, providing ample space for strolling or relaxing by the water. Whether you're looking to read a book or simply enjoy the tranquil surroundings, this riverside promenade is an ideal spot to unwind and soak in the city's atmosphere.
name: Quai des Bateliers

detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Strasbourg, Église Saint-Louis de Strasbourg is a serene oasis away from the city's hustle and bustle. This personal parish is particularly cherished for its Tridentine mass, which fosters an atmosphere of sacredness and reflection. The church's interior captivates visitors with stunning stained glass windows, a historic altarpiece, and murals depicting King Saint-Louis. While its exterior may seem understated at first glance, stepping inside reveals refined classical architecture adorned with exquisite baroque furnishings.
name: Église Saint-Louis de Strasbourg

detail_description: The Musée d'Art Moderne & Contemporain is housed in a modern building along the Ill River, offering a bright and spacious 10,000-square-meter gallery space. It features an extensive collection of 19th- and 20th-century paintings by renowned artists such as Picasso, Monet, Kandinsky, and more. The museum also hosts temporary exhibitions showcasing surprising works of art. Admission fees apply but are reduced for certain visitors.
name: Musée d'Art Moderne

detail_description: Maison des Ponts Couverts, located in Strasbourg, Alsace, is a private estate used as a child rehabilitation center. Situated between the 'Spitzmuhl' and 'Duntzmuhl' canals, it offers an idyllic setting by the water's edge. This house serves as a neutral meeting place for parents and children going through difficult times. The picturesque building is surrounded by rivers and makes for stunning photo opportunities throughout the year.
name: Maison des Ponts Couverts

detail_description: Parc de la Citadelle is a beautiful urban park located in the heart of the city. It offers a peaceful escape from the hustle and bustle of urban life, with its lush greenery and tranquil atmosphere. The park features a large lake where visitors can rent boats and enjoy a leisurely paddle on the water. There are also walking paths, perfect for a relaxing stroll or jog amidst nature.
name: Parc de la Citadelle

excerpt: Burgers, salads, French dishes & drinks in a chic cafe with al fresco tables by the water.
detail_description: La Corde à Linge is a popular restaurant located in the heart of La Petite France in Strasbourg. Despite its touristy appearance, locals appreciate its large waterfront terrace and traditional Alsatian dishes such as spatzle. The restaurant offers a solid menu featuring Alsatian, French, and Continental cuisine. With a charming setting and the option to dine al fresco by the river Ill, it's an ideal spot for lunch or dinner while exploring Strasbourg.
name: La Corde à Linge

detail_description: La Popartiserie is not your typical coffee shop; it's a unique art gallery that has become a popular destination for art and pop culture enthusiasts. Visitors can enjoy the exhibitions without feeling pressured to make any purchases, making it an unconventional spot to savor a beverage. The venue also hosts performances, such as live music events on Saturday nights, creating a vibrant atmosphere.
name: La Popartiserie

detail_description: The Office de Tourisme Strasbourg et sa Région is conveniently located near the Notre Dame cathedral and Maison Kammerzell. Visitors can obtain the Strasbourg city card, which includes a booklet with a map and lists of major attractions, as well as a comprehensive town guide. The friendly and multilingual staff provide helpful information on local events, hotel accommodations, transportation options, and even the wine route.
name: Office de Tourisme Strasbourg et sa Région
address: 17 Pl. de la Cathédrale, 67082 Strasbourg, France

detail_description: The Bains Municipaux de Strasbourg offers a variety of experiences, from the Roman baths to the swimming pool. Visitors can enjoy the Hammam at Les Cent Ciels or try the unique Taaka Beer Spa. The facility has both old and newly renovated sections, with stylish Nordic pools and saunas in the modern area, while the old section boasts Roman pools in marble and traditional saunas.
name: Bains Municipaux de Strasbourg
address: 10 Bd de la Victoire, 67000 Strasbourg, France

detail_description: The Synagogue de la Paix, built in 1954 to replace the original synagogue destroyed by the Nazis, stands as an important landmark for Strasbourg's Jewish community dating back to the 12th century. While lacking the grandeur of its predecessor, it serves as a significant place of worship. The surrounding Parc du Contades offers a peaceful retreat with leafy pathways ideal for leisurely strolls.
name: Synagogue de la Paix

excerpt: An upscale residential neighborhood, Orangerie centers on its flower-filled namesake park, with walking trails, a boating lake, and play areas, plus events at Pavillon Joséphine. Storks roam the park, and a small zoo is home to macaques and ibises. Ice-cream vendors and a mix of casual and upmarket restaurants dot the park and beyond, while art nouveau and Renaissance Revival villas line Allée de la Robertsau.
detail_description: Orangerie, an elegant neighborhood in Strasbourg, is named after its beautiful park filled with flowers and walking trails. The park features a boating lake, play areas, and hosts events at Pavillon Joséphine. Storks can be spotted roaming the area while a small zoo houses macaques and ibises. The district is also home to European institutions like the Council of Europe and the European Parliament, making it perfect for those interested in politics or international relations.
name: Orangerie

excerpt: Unique 1800s clock providing both astronomical & calendrical information in Strasbourg Cathedral.
detail_description: The Strasbourg Cathedral houses a remarkable 1800s clock that displays both astronomical and calendrical information. This sophisticated clock is located on the left side of the cathedral and features a robot that moves and makes a warning sound every hour. The clock's creation was an innovative achievement in the past, garnering much attention to this day.
name: Astronomical Clock
address: 17 Pl. de la Cathédrale CEDEX, 67082 Strasbourg, France
